description: Five Violet-green Swallows (Tachycineta thalassina), roosting on an overhead wire near the Visitors Center and the Jasper Ridge Biological Preserve in central San Mateo County, CA.  This overhead wire appeared to be a popular roosting spot for these swallows, who were migrating through the area in late September as they headed for their wintering grounds.  Dozens of them would gather on this wire in the evenings, and still be present for an hour or so after sunrise.

The galls of three Saucer Gall Wasps (Andricus gigas), photographed on the leaf of a Blue Oak hybrid (Querus douglasii X) that I found at the Jasper RIdge Biological Preserve in central San Mateo County, CA. Identification based on visual similarity with photographs of the galls of A. gigas available online; see References below.

1) "California Oak Galls," Joyce Gross, Joyce Gross Photography.  Retrieved from http://joycegross.com/galls_ca_oak.php on 1/15/18.

3.  "Species Andricus gigas - Saucer Gall Wasp," Bug Guide.  Retrieved from https://bugguide.net/node/view/130818 on 1/16/19.

description:
Small group of highly confusing oaks. Mature trees to 20 feet tall, but have ridiculously vicious leaf-spines on all the leaves. Characters seem to put them in the Intermediate Oaks, which, for the SC Mtns region, would make it canyon oak, Q. chrysolepis.

But the leaf-spines, which are far more needle-like than any we can find on Q. chrysolepis in the SC Mtns, in combo with the roundish, wavy leaves and warble-edged acorn cups suggest Q. palmeri. Even the branching pattern and bark seem similar to palmeri.

But the nearest occurrences of Q. palmeri are in the East Bay in Sunol. Nor are there any other known Q. chrysolepis on the preserve for a localized comparison.

Oaks!
place_guess: Jasper Ridge Biological Preserve, San Mateo County, CA, USA
